 `Object[]` arrays rather than `GenericArrayType`. I need a generic parameter but want to avoid the need for casting. I could access it using a raw type, like `List<?> values = ((GenericArrayListBean<?>) result).values;` which would help eliminate the need to cast to `String[]`. \\n\\nI'm curious if using `beanFrom` on `StringArrayListBean` would produce `Object[]` elements, which seems likely. That would make assertions on casting to `Object[]` valid. I could also consider implementing a getter in the generic superclass for `List<T[]> getValues()`. Would that simplify access through raw or wildcard types? Maybe using something like `assertThat(values).extracting(array -> (Object[]) array)` could be a clearer way to read elements individually. I also want to check if I should mark nested classes as static final, given that only top-level classes need to be public. Lastly, I'm pondering if there could be deserialization issues with `List<T[]>` since the collectionReader chooses the value reader based on the erased type.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Adjusting ArrayReader imports**\\n\\nI’m considering how the ArrayReader will handle nested arrays as `Object[]` with AnyReader values. Strings will turn into String objects, which is encouraging. I think I need to edit the imports accordingly. Perhaps it’s best to remove the previous TypeResolver import, but actually, I might still need it. I'll get rid of the reflection imports, though. I should also add JSON and List imports, and keep the Type import for the helper `Type componentType`. Time to craft this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing generic array type**\\n\\nI'm working on implementing a generic array type using a functional interface, given that `GenericArrayType` has a single abstract method for retrieving the component type. While I could use a lambda, an anonymous class might be clearer. I decide to create a cleaner implementation with a static method that returns a new instance of `SimpleGenericArrayType`.\\n\\nNext, I think about adding a second test to handle deserializing bean properties with generic array elements. I need to focus on ensuring my public API is clean and avoid direct reflection where possible. Once that’s done, I’ll edit and commit my changes cautiously, given the other modified files in the repo.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Uqe6geOpuvsTEXlb2RaknJy8|fc_068fd484880648cf0169f031d48690819491c3b428d82e5024", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/src/test/java/com_fasterxml_jackson_jr/jackson_jr_objects/TypeResolverDynamicAccessTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "package com_fasterxml_jackson_jr.jackson_jr_objects;\n\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.type.ResolvedType;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.type.TypeBindings;\nimport com.fasterxml.jackson.jr.type.TypeResolver;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\nimport java.lang.reflect.GenericArrayType;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Type;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class TypeResolverDynamicAccessTest {\n    @Test\n    void resolvesGenericArrayTypesFromUnboundTypeVariables() throws Exception {\n        TypeResolver resolver = new TypeResolver();\n        Type genericArrayType = GenericArrayContainer.class.getDeclaredField(\"values\").getGenericType();\n\n        assertThat(genericArrayType).isInstanceOf(GenericArrayType.class);\n\n        ResolvedType resolvedArrayType = resolver.resolve(TypeBindings.emptyBindings(), genericArrayType);\n\n        assertThat(resolvedArrayType.isArray()).isTrue();\n        assertThat(resolvedArrayType.erasedType()).isEqualTo(Object[].class);\n        assertThat(resolvedArrayType.elementType().erasedType()).isEqualTo(Object.class);\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void resolvesGenericArrayTypesFromBoundTypeVariables() throws Exception {\n        TypeResolver resolver = new TypeResolver();\n        ResolvedType declaringType = resolver.resolve